1. Clarify Requirements

Before designing, ask clarifying questions.

Functional Requirements
The system should:
Send notifications to users

Support multiple channels:

  Email
  SMS
  Push notifications
  In-app notifications
  Trigger notifications based on events
  Support bulk notifications
  Allow users to manage preferences

Example events:
  Task assigned
  Password reset
  New message

Non-Functional Requirements
  High scalability
  Low latency
  High availability
  Fault tolerance
  Guaranteed delivery (at least once)

2. Estimate Scale

  Example assumptions:
  Users = 100M
  Daily active users = 10M
  Notifications per user per day:
  10 notifications
  Total per day:
  10M × 10 = 100M notifications/day
  Peak traffic:
  ~3000 notifications/sec

So the system must support thousands of requests per second.

3. High-Level Architecture

    Core architecture:
    
    Client Applications
            |
    Application Servers
            |
    Notification Service
            |
    Message Queue
            |
    ----------------------------------
    Email Worker
    SMS Worker
    Push Worker
    In-App Worker
    ----------------------------------
            |
    External Providers / Databases

4. Key Components
1. Notification Service

This service:

receives notification requests

validates payload

stores notification

pushes event to queue

Example API:

POST /notifications

Payload example:

{
 "userId": "123",
 "channel": "EMAIL",
 "message": "Task assigned to you"
}
2. Message Queue

Queues decouple services.

Benefits:

async processing

retry capability

traffic smoothing

Common technologies:

Kafka

RabbitMQ

AWS SQS

Flow:

Notification Service
        |
      Queue
        |
   Worker Services
3. Worker Services

Separate workers for each channel.

Email Worker

Sends emails via providers.

SMS Worker

Sends messages via telecom APIs.

Push Worker

Sends mobile push notifications.

In-App Worker

Stores notifications in the database.

5. Database Design

Two main tables.

Notifications Table
notifications
--------------
notification_id
user_id
type
channel
message
status
created_at
User Preferences
user_preferences
----------------
user_id
email_enabled
sms_enabled
push_enabled

This allows users to control notification settings.

6. Event Driven Flow
Example: Task assigned

    Task Service
         |
    Event Published
         |
    Notification Service
         |
    Message Queue
         |
    Workers
         |
    Send Notification
7. Handling Failures

    Workers may fail.
    Solutions:
    Retry Mechanism
    If sending fails:
    Retry 3 times
    Dead Letter Queue
    If retries fail:
    Message → Dead Letter Queue
    For debugging.

8. Rate Limiting

    To avoid spamming users.
    Example rule:
    Max 5 notifications per minute per user
    Implemented using:
      Redis counters

9. Scheduling Notifications

  Some notifications are delayed.
  Example:
  Reminder after 24 hours
  Use:
  Scheduled jobs
  Delayed queues

10. Scaling Strategy
    Horizontal Scaling
    Workers scale independently.
    Queue
     |
    Multiple Workers
    Database Scaling
    
    Use:
    partitioning by user ID
    read replicas
    Caching
    Redis caches:
    user preferences
    notification templates

11. Notification Templates
Store templates for reusable messages.

