1. How Notification Syncing Works Across Multiple Devices

    Users often access apps from multiple devices:
    Phone
    Laptop
    Tablet
    
    To keep notifications consistent, systems use server-based storage + device syncing.
    
    Basic Sync Architecture
    User Action
         |
    Notification Service
         |
    Notification Database
         |
    Push Notification
         |
    Device receives alert
         |
    User opens app
         |
    App fetches notifications from server
    
    Key idea:
    
    👉 Server stores the notification history
    👉 Devices fetch updates when needed
    
    Multi-Device Sync Flow
    
    Example: user gets a notification.
    
    Event Created
         |
    Notification Stored in DB
         |
    Push sent to all user devices
         |
    Devices receive notification
    
    Devices registered:
    
      UserID: 1001
      Device1: iPhone
      Device2: Laptop
      Device3: Tablet
    
    When a notification is created:
    
      Send push → iPhone
      Send push → Laptop
      Send push → Tablet
      Read Status Sync
    
    If the user reads the notification on one device:
    
    User opens notification on phone
            |
    Server updates status → READ
            |
    Other devices sync
            |
    Notification disappears or marked read
    Techniques Used
    
    Large systems use:
      Device tokens
      WebSockets
      Long polling
      Push services
    
    Example push providers:
    Apple Push Notification service
    Firebase Cloud Messaging

2. How Companies Store Billions of Notifications Efficiently

Companies like Meta Platforms handle billions of notifications daily, so efficient storage is critical.

    Database Schema Example
    notifications
    --------------
    notification_id
    user_id
    type
    message
    status
    created_at
    Data Partitioning (Sharding)
    
    Instead of one huge database, data is split across many servers.
    
    Example:
    
    Shard 1 → users 1–1M
    Shard 2 → users 1M–2M
    Shard 3 → users 2M–3M
    
    This reduces database load.
    
    Time-Based Partitioning
    
    Notifications can be stored by date partitions.
    Example:
    
    notifications_2026_jan
    notifications_2026_feb
    notifications_2026_mar
    
    Benefits:
    faster queries
    easier archiving
    Archiving Old Notifications
    Old data moves to cheaper storage.
    
    Example flow:
    
    Recent notifications → Fast database
    Old notifications → Data warehouse / cold storage
    Compression and Batching
    
    Instead of storing many small notifications:
    
    Example:
    
    User liked your post
    User liked your post
    User liked your post
    
    Systems aggregate them:
    10 people liked your post
    This reduces storage.

3. How Message Queues Handle Large Notification Traffic

Message queues allow systems to process millions of notifications asynchronously.

    Common technologies:
    Apache Kafka
    RabbitMQ
    AWS SQS
    
    Basic Queue Architecture
    Application Service
          |
    Message Queue
          |
    Worker Services
          |
    Notification Sent
    Why Queues Are Important
    
    Queues solve three major problems:

1. Traffic Spikes

    Example spike:
    Black Friday sale
    Millions of notifications triggered.
    Queue buffers traffic:
    
  Requests → Queue → Workers process gradually
2. Asynchronous Processing

    Without queue:
    App waits until notification sent
    With queue:
    App pushes message to queue
    App continues immediately
    This improves performance.

3. Parallel Processing

    Workers can scale horizontally.
    
    Queue
     |
    Worker1
    Worker2
    Worker3
    Worker4

    Each worker processes notifications independently.
    Queue Partitioning
    Large systems partition queues.
    Example:
    
    Partition1 → userID % 4 = 0
    Partition2 → userID % 4 = 1
    Partition3 → userID % 4 = 2
    Partition4 → userID % 4 = 3

    This distributes load.
    Retry and Failure Handling
    If sending fails:
    Retry → Retry Queue → Dead Letter Queue
    Dead letter queue stores failed messages for investigation.
    End-to-End Notification Pipeline

    A typical large-scale notification flow:
    
    User Action
         |
    Application Service
         |
    Event Queue (Kafka)
         |
    Notification Service
         |
    Channel Workers
         |
    Push / Email / SMS Providers
         |
    User Devices

